# Purpose

This rule governs how Smart Wearable Technology (SWT) self-citations are sourced, selected, and rendered in every `CAN_lab.X/paper/<slug>/main.tex` in this repository, and how the officially supplied publication spreadsheet under `CAN_lab.X/paper/_etc/` is kept replaceable without breaking downstream `main.tex` files.
It complements `latex-inst.mdc` (writing voice and ethics) and `microchip-can-paper-workflow.mdc` (folder layout, slug convention, bibliography hygiene).
Follow this rule whenever a new manuscript is scaffolded, an existing manuscript's bibliography is revised, or the spreadsheet in `CAN_lab.X/paper/_etc/` is refreshed by the official.

# Rule precedence

When guidance from multiple sources collides, precedence resolves in this order:

1. The MDPI journal template (for example `Definitions/mdpi.cls`) controls structural tokens and the `\bibitem` macro surface.
2. `microchip-can-paper-workflow.mdc` controls folder layout, slug convention, label prefixes, figure manifests, acronym discipline, ethics-block templates, and overall bibliography hygiene.
3. `swt-citation-policy.mdc` (this rule) controls the SWT-specific citation-source contract, the exact-three requirement, and the retraction block.
4. `latex-inst.mdc` controls prose voice, forbidden words, paragraph rhythm, and the pre-commit writing checklist.

Any deviation from a higher-priority rule must be documented in the plan file before execution.

# Source-of-truth file invariant

The folder `CAN_lab.X/paper/_etc/` carries the official SWT publication and retraction spreadsheet plus one LaTeX tutorial sheet.
The spreadsheet is the single source of truth for every SWT self-citation in this repository.

## Plug-and-play contract

The filename the official uses varies by quarter (for example `【SCOPUS+SCI】wearable device-related-Y26Q2.xlsx` for the second quarter of 2026, then `...-Y26Q3.xlsx`, `...-Y26Q4.xlsx`, `...-Y27Q1.xlsx`, and so on).
This rule pins the glob, not the filename, so a quarterly refresh is a drop-in replacement:

```
CAN_lab.X/paper/_etc/*.xlsx
```

The single-file invariant is strict: the match set of `CAN_lab.X/paper/_etc/*.xlsx` has cardinality exactly one at every commit that mentions an SWT citation.
When a new quarterly file arrives, the previous `.xlsx` is deleted in the same change that adds the new one; the repository never carries two SWT spreadsheets simultaneously, so there is no ambiguity about which file is authoritative.

The non-xlsx file `tutorial_sheet.tex` is permitted to coexist in `CAN_lab.X/paper/_etc/`; only `*.xlsx` files are constrained by the single-file invariant.
Backup copies of the spreadsheet (for example `*-Y26Q2.xlsx.bak`) are also forbidden in this folder; if an archive of prior quarters is required, store it outside the repository or behind a `.gitignore` rule that excludes `CAN_lab.X/paper/_etc/archive/`.

## Sheet contract

The spreadsheet contains exactly two sheets.
Both sheet names are fixed; the official refresh preserves the sheet names verbatim.

| Sheet        | Role                                                                                                                       |
| ------------ | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `SWT`        | Candidate pool. Every SWT self-citation must correspond to a row in this sheet. Column `Citation Format` is the canonical citation string. |
| `retraction` | Hard block list. A DOI appearing in this sheet's `Citation Format` column must never appear in any `main.tex` in the repository, even when it reappears in a future quarter's `SWT` sheet. |

The `SWT` sheet also carries four editorial rules in rows 35--38; these are imported below.

## Refresh procedure

When the official releases a new quarterly spreadsheet, perform the following in a single commit:

1. Delete the previous `CAN_lab.X/paper/_etc/*.xlsx` in the same change that adds the new one.
2. Re-run the pre-commit verification snippet (see below) against every `CAN_lab.X/paper/<slug>/main.tex`.
3. If any cited SWT article now appears in the new `retraction` sheet, replace that `\bibitem` with another `SWT`-sheet entry of similar topical fit, update the corresponding `\cite{...}` inline, and rerun the verification.
4. Copy `Citation Format` strings verbatim from the new spreadsheet; do not paraphrase.

Each manuscript's bibliography therefore stays a pure projection of the current spreadsheet with no manual intermediate representation.

# Exact-three rule

Every `CAN_lab.X/paper/<slug>/main.tex` cites exactly three articles drawn from the current `SWT` sheet.
Two SWT citations is a violation; four SWT citations is a violation.
The rule applies to every existing manuscript and to every future manuscript scaffolded under `CAN_lab.X/paper/<slug>/`.

## Selection heuristic

The three SWT articles chosen for a given manuscript are the three with the strongest topical fit to the manuscript's contribution, subject to the retraction-block and rule-6 constraints below.
Overlap between sibling manuscripts is permitted as long as no single SWT lead-author surname appears in more than two of the repository's `main.tex` files (this keeps the aggregate contribution to rule 6 below 20%).

## Retraction block

